        <strong>Hericenones (Fruiting Body)</strong>
        <p>Found primarily in the fruiting body. Cross the blood-brain barrier and stimulate NGF synthesis. The primary bioactive compounds responsible for lion's mane cognitive benefits in clinical studies.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Erinacines (Mycelium)</strong>
        <p>Found in the mycelium. Also stimulate NGF production but are typically present in lower concentrations in commercial mycelium-on-grain supplements due to grain starch dilution.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Beta-Glucans</strong>
        <p>Polysaccharides that support immune function. Fruiting body extracts contain 20-40% beta-glucans. A beta-glucan content below 15% often indicates grain filler rather than genuine mushroom material.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Fruiting Body vs Mycelium</strong>
        <p>Fruiting body = the actual mushroom. Mycelium-on-grain = root network grown on rice or oat substrate. Products labeled "mycelium" often contain 50-70% grain starch by weight. Always verify the source.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

