    <!-- SCIENCE DEEP DIVE -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h3>Lion's Mane Science: Hericenones, Erinacines, and Nerve Growth Factor</h3>
      <p>Understanding the bioactive compounds in lion's mane and how they affect the brain is essential for evaluating whether a particular product can deliver real cognitive benefits or is simply selling mushroom-flavored candy.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Nerve Growth Factor (NGF)</strong>
          <p>A protein critical for neuron survival, differentiation, and synaptic plasticity. NGF levels decline with age, correlating with cognitive decline and neurodegenerative disease progression. Lion's mane is the only known dietary source of compounds that directly stimulate NGF synthesis.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Hericenones (A-H)</strong>
          <p>Found primarily in the fruiting body. These aromatic compounds cross the blood-brain barrier and induce NGF gene expression in astrocyte cells. Hericenones C and D are the most studied for NGF activity. Requires alcohol extraction to isolate effectively.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Erinacines (A-K)</strong>
          <p>Found primarily in the mycelium. Diterpenoid compounds that also stimulate NGF synthesis but through different pathways than hericenones. Erinacine A is the most potent NGF inducer identified. Rarely quantified on commercial product labels.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Beta-Glucans</strong>
          <p>Polysaccharides that modulate immune function by activating macrophages and natural killer cells. Not directly related to cognitive function but provide systemic immune support. Content above 20% indicates genuine mushroom material; below 15% suggests grain dilution.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

