    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Lion's Mane Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does lion's mane actually improve memory and focus?</summary>
      <p>Multiple clinical studies support lion's mane for cognitive function. A 2009 double-blind, placebo-controlled trial in <em>Phytotherapy Research</em> found that adults aged 50-80 who took 3g daily for 16 weeks showed significantly improved cognitive function scores compared to placebo. A 2020 study in the <em>Journal of Medicinal Food</em> found improvements in short-term memory and concentration in healthy adults after 12 weeks. The mechanism involves hericenones and erinacines that stimulate Nerve Growth Factor (NGF) synthesis in the brain.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between fruiting body and mycelium in lion's mane supplements?</summary>
      <p>The fruiting body is the visible mushroom containing the highest concentrations of hericenones and beta-glucans. Mycelium is the root network grown on grain substrate (usually rice or oats). Mycelium-on-grain products contain significant grain starch filler, sometimes 50-70% of product weight, with lower concentrations of active compounds. Most clinical studies use fruiting body extracts. Choose products specifying "100% fruiting body" or disclosing beta-glucan content above 20%.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for lion's mane gummies to work?</summary>
      <p>Most users report noticeable improvements in focus and mental clarity within 2-4 weeks of daily use. Clinical studies showing significant cognitive improvements run 8-16 weeks. Lion's mane stimulates NGF production, which is a gradual biological process. Commit to at least 8 weeks before evaluating effectiveness. Some users report subtle improvements in mood and clarity within the first week.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What dosage of lion's mane is clinically effective?</summary>
      <p>Clinical studies use 500mg to 3,000mg per day of fruiting body extract. The most commonly cited effective dose is 1,000mg per day of standardized extract containing measurable hericenones and beta-glucans. Most gummies provide 500-1,000mg per serving. Higher doses have not shown adverse effects in studies lasting up to 16 weeks. If your gummy provides 500mg, taking two servings daily to reach 1,000mg is a reasonable approach.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take lion's mane with other nootropics or supplements?</summary>
      <p>Lion's mane is generally safe to combine with other supplements. Common stacks include lion's mane + cordyceps (energy + focus), lion's mane + reishi (cognition + calm), and lion's mane + caffeine + L-theanine for enhanced acute focus. No known dangerous interactions exist with common supplements. However, lion's mane may have mild anticoagulant properties — consult your physician if taking blood thinners.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are lion's mane gummies safe? Are there any side effects?</summary>
      <p>Lion's mane has an excellent safety profile in clinical trials lasting up to 16 weeks at doses up to 3,000mg per day. The most common side effects are mild GI discomfort in a small percentage of users during the first few days. Individuals with mushroom allergies should avoid lion's mane. Those on blood thinners, immunosuppressants, or diabetes medications should consult a healthcare provider before use.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are hericenones and erinacines in lion's mane?</summary>
      <p>Hericenones and erinacines are bioactive compounds found exclusively in <em>Hericium erinaceus</em>. Hericenones (found in the fruiting body) and erinacines (found in the mycelium) both stimulate NGF production. NGF is a protein critical for neuron growth, maintenance, and survival. By promoting NGF synthesis, these compounds support neuroplasticity, memory formation, and protection against age-related cognitive decline.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take lion's mane in the morning or at night?</summary>
      <p>Most users take lion's mane in the morning or early afternoon for daytime cognitive support. Unlike caffeine, lion's mane has no stimulant properties and will not disrupt sleep. Some users report enhanced dream vividness when taking it near bedtime. Timing does not significantly affect efficacy — daily consistency matters more. For productivity-focused use, morning dosing aligns peak effects with your workday.</p>
    </details>

